The latest test results for establishing the age limit for asylum applications in Sweden
The latest results of asylum seekers' tests in Sweden, who have been subjected to a new method assessing their age, show that over 80 percent of people have been questioned as over 18 years of age, but not everyone believes their accuracy.
The Swedish forensics medical agency (Rôttsmedicinalverket) began to perform new tests at the beginning of this year.
The aim of the method is a more accurate assessment of applicants in the context of the evaluation of asylum applications. The measure was taken after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticised for failure to determine the correct age of some refugees who lied about their age.
As of today, the Swedish migration agency has presented the results for the investigation of 6880 cases and the forensic medical agency has now published the results of a total of 2481 tests carried out from mid March to 31 July 2017.
80 percent (2002) were assessed as over 18 years of age, while in the next 25 cases, the forensic medical agency considered that the question was “probably over 18 years of age”.
In another 423 cases, it was decided that the asked one was “probably under 18 years of age”.
The tests shall only be used if the age of the contested person is disputed.
According to Johan Gêsransson from the forensic medical agency, the results correspond to the previous month.
"Compared to last month's statistics are kept in the tracks and numbers are very similar," said The Local.
A higher number of candidates whose age was estimated to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers lie about their age.
In May, the Agency published the results of 581 tests and stated that in 442 cases ‘the person concerned is 18 years of age or older’.
The papers of Svenska Dagbladet investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases the questionnaire stated that it would be 18 years old this year.
The criteria have also been met by a medical method for determining the age, which includes the X-rays of the teeth of wisdom and MRI of the knee joints, which subsequently assess dentists and X-rayologists.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, which deals, among other things, with the assessment of the biological maturity of people to determine the age when the person has undergone puberty.
“I had reason to think about this issue, and I do not think these types of measurements to assess age are correct.
The assessment of biological age is, in a sense, very uncertain.
If we cannot determine the age with accuracy, we should not pretend otherwise," the Metro newspaper said.
The forensic medical agency Agency’s Gêšransson defended the decision by saying: “In general, it can be said that the risk of wrong assessment of a child as an adult is small.
The highest risk is the fact that the person in question is just below the 18-year-old limit, which in this case corresponds to 10 percent of everyone in question."
