Pre-exposure prophylaxis (Prep) is an HIV medicine taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PREP significantly reduces the risk of transmission of HIV to vulnerable patients.
Pre-sex application means that there are sufficient specific medicines in the patient’s body to prevent infection.
These medicines can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Test patients include gay or bisexual men, transsexual people and people with HIV positive partners who are not successfully treated.
The clinics shall identify eligible participants who will sign approval to participate in the testing, including men, women, transsexual people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GP in the UK can also apply to their local clinic of sexual health and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program will bring taxpayers to £10 million and the NHS of England signed a drug distribution contract this week after obtaining an international public contract.
The trial period is proposed for the collection of clinical evidence and assessment of the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: “This important intervention should complement and make full use of the constantly expanding and increasingly successful effort to prevent HIV.
