Startups that will help your company not to become the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the satisfaction of the employees of her e-commerce startup, but she didn't find a suitable survey.
The answers were often imprecise, useless, or even deceptive.
And even though she promised anonymity of the survey, some employees expressed their mistrust in the whole process.
"I looked for consistency and objectivity," said Errett, owner of an e-commerce hair care company Madison Reed, based in San Francisco, employing 75 people.
So she asked for help from the outside.
New startups from the human resources sector are constantly emerging on the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with a specific intention of measuring employees' responsibilities, companies allow companies to make quick votes, target specific teams and demographic groups, further offers complete anonymity of employees and a hot line of complaints, and in some cases they also allow informants to go around and contact the director directly.
"There are tools on the market such as the Strava and Fitbit that follow your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of the Glint startup, based in Reedwood City.
Errett said that, in three years' time, Glint gained greater awareness of what her employees thought and what they felt.
In addition to quick surveys and votes of specific teams, Glint offers a company's temperature map and a regular overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of managers with low ratings - which allows the user to work on the axle.
The companies are beginning to realize that it is necessary to care for the culture of the working environment - in case they become another Uber - which is thrown away in scandals after the former employee published a contribution to his blog describing the corporate environment and harassment of employees who dare to speak openly.
For startups such as Glint, the demand for surveys of corporate culture represents a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the Let's Talk Payments website, which deals with technical and financial progress, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance sector by 2020 can exceed $118.8 billion.
Explosion Converter from Denver, Colorado, who helps companies to prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a slight increase in interest and activity at the beginning of the year, just before the Uber scandals.
Almost 600 Converter clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
He recently accepted Uber under his wings.
Like Glint, the Converter allows companies to send customised flash surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If the Director-General is involved in the problem, complaints shall be sent directly to the Governing Board.
“The Court of Justice has authorised regulators,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of the Converter startup.
If the company is convicted of mistreatment with its employees or non-ethical behavior - and if regulators do not act - it may face costly consequences due to the boycott of customers, the exhaustion of employees or judicial proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday network employs more than 25,000 people across 500 locations, using Converter for more than a year to raise the awareness of corporate principles and procedures and ensure an easy way to contact corporate leadership.
Before that, if the employee wanted to report any problems, he had to track the phone number or e-mail to the management of the company, officially file a complaint and hope for a successful solution.
It was often a horrifying and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, Deputy General Ruby Tuesday, who previously did not have a reliable way of monitoring employee complaints.
Now that the company is using the Converter, it is ensured that there is rapid detection and resolution of problems that have never previously gone to managers sitting in offices, miles away from the actual solution to complaints - for example, discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
“This is coming to a holistic overall view of the experience of employees,” said Vitrano, who is managing Ruby Tuesday’s risk management group.
"At the same time, we protect shareholders from legal disputes by employees."
The companies stopped taking the ethics, values and employee participation lightly in 2002 after Arthur Andersen’s accountants collapsed after Enron’s collapse in the case of the abuse of the ethical rights of employees, Quinlan said.
But only when “the social media lit the whole thing” began to realize that in the online world they could not simply hide their skeletons in a closet.
"Before people started using ethics to follow, they relied on faith," added Quinlan.
Glint and Converter offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It is a business model and an opportunity approved by bold capital investors who supported both startups.
As part of his February campaign, Converter chose $10 million in total from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital and eventually he took the capital of $47 million.
Glint received $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and received $60 million during the entire campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of companies, culture and risk capital.
The growing number of research clearly confirms that today’s employees expect more than ever from their workplace.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, the main advantage is not high wages and interesting projects.
Employees want to believe that they are received and appreciated and that they devote their time to a company that seeks a positive mission.
“If people are happy in their work, they feel that their voice is heard, and that their work is rewarding, they seek the success of society,” said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefit and employee benefits of LinkedIn, which uses Converter and Glint.
Investors earn if companies and companies are successful if their employees are satisfied.
And when an analytical tool appears on the market to ensure the commitment and commitment of employees to the company, it is no wonder that there are many investors who will support this effort.
According to work culture experts, it is important to have staff satisfaction data.
But the data itself is impeccable unless the company takes the necessary steps.
The fact is, once the company requests feedback from its employees, there may be major changes.
And if change does not happen quickly - in the worst case ever - it may cause disappointment and disinterest of employees.
"As soon as you ask for 4,000 opinions, you must be prepared for 4,000 conversations," said Russell Raath, director of consulting at Kotter International, who witnessed many companies that were too relying on data alone.
“ Because once things are not done, employees start asking themselves: ‘ Did they hear me at all?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, why should I care?'"
Madison Reed, now regularly conducting a survey between employees every month, is able to solve the problem through Glint within one day, said Errett.
After the assembly of feedback from employees who were frustrated by slow decision making and communication quality, Errett was able to reorganise several teams within the company and start training communication for a successful solution to the problem.
Ruby Tuesday receives a very important view of its employees and hopes that in the long run it will achieve high employment in the field known to be frequent redundancies.
"If you do not seek a transparent working environment, employees will not believe you," said Vitrano.
"And as soon as you lose your employees, you lose your customers.
